phases.instructions:
First, create a bar chart showing quarterly sales data using create_plotly. Make it dark mode with a black background - and give it some artistic flair! Use this data as a template:

```json
{"tool": "create_chart", "arguments": {"chart_type": "bar", "title": "Quarterly Sales by Region", "data": {"labels": ["North", "South", "East", "West"], "values": [125000, 98500, 142000, 87200]}, "xlabel": "Region", "ylabel": "Revenue ($)"}}
```

Then, after the chart is created, call ask_human_custom to demonstrate a two-column composite UI. The auto_detect feature will automatically include the chart you just created. Use this call:

```json
{
  "tool": "ask_human_custom",
  "arguments": {
    "question": "Does this sales analysis look accurate?",
    "context": "I analyzed the Q4 2024 sales data and generated this chart. The data shows strong growth in the North and East regions, with a slight decline in the West region. Overall revenue increased by 12% compared to Q3.",
    "data": {
      "Regional Performance": [
        {"Region": "North", "Revenue": "$125,000", "Growth": "+15%", "Target Met": "Yes"},
        {"Region": "South", "Revenue": "$98,500", "Growth": "+8%", "Target Met": "Yes"},
        {"Region": "East", "Revenue": "$142,000", "Growth": "+22%", "Target Met": "Yes"},
        {"Region": "West", "Revenue": "$87,200", "Growth": "-3%", "Target Met": "No"}
      ]
    },
    "ui_hint": "confirmation",
    "layout_hint": "two-column"
  }
}
```
